                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 812.00/12691.</note>
                <head ana="#head_untitled-inferred-from-preceding-sibling-head">[Untitled]</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Saltillo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-07-30">
                            <hi rend="italic">July 30, 1914</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Governor Carranza’s Secretary for Foreign Relations, Fabela, called attention
                    today to what he terms a distinction between armistice and suspension of
                    military operations. The latter, as in the present instance, may be a voluntary
                    concession. On arrival of Carbajal envoys with proper credentials and authority,
                    military operations [omission] suspended as announced. But an armistice is not
                    under consideration. It is an altogether different relation and presupposes a
                    pact or agreement, which in the present instance has not been contemplated.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Silliman</hi>
                    </signed>.</closer>
            </div>
        </body>
